ts-based interpretation of private property entrenches the idea of human dominion over nature. Accordingly, nature is not attributed any inherent value and becomes merely the matter of a human property relationship. Earth Jurisprudence: Private Property and the Environment explores how an alternative conception of property might be instead grounded in the eco-centric concept of an Earth community. Recognising that human beings are deeply interconnected with and dependent on nature, this concept is proposed as a standard and measure for human law. Using the theory of Earth Jurisprudence as a guide, this book outlines an alternative eco-centric description of private property, as a relationship between and among members of the Earth community"--cProvided by publisher.  a45 0aRight of property. 0aEnvironmental lawxPhilosophy. 0aProperty. 0aConservation of natural resourcesxLaw and legislation. 0aLawxPhilosophy. 0aLaw, justice and ecology.423Cover imageuhttp://images.tandf.co.uk/common/jackets/websmall/978041563/9780415633178.jpg  aK 721.5 B87 2015c1hUALA-Bi0162035223906  aK 721.5 B87 2015wLCc1i0162035223906lON_SHELFmUALAWp$150.00rYsYtBOOKu1/14/201501ahttp://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/nb2012019047bhttp://viaf.org/viaf/220562405